=begin pod

=head1 5. Validation and Constraints

This is where the Slangify approach becomes more valuable than plain prompting.
Constraints live in the grammar and the C<Booking> class — not in the prompt.

=head2 Tightening grammar tokens

Restrict C<party> to one or two digits (no absurdly large parties):

=begin code :lang<raku>
token party { <[1..9]> \d? }   # 1–99
=end code

Restrict C<time> to valid 24-hour ranges:

=begin code :lang<raku>
token time { <[0..2]>\d ':' <[0..5]>\d }
=end code

Any LLM output that violates these rules causes the grammar to fail — the
error surfaces before the result reaches your application.

=head2 Constraints in the Booking class

Use Raku's type system and C<TWEAK> for business-rule validation:

=begin code :lang<raku>
class Booking does Actionable {
    has Str $.name;
    has Int $.party where 1 <= * <= 20;   # range constraint
    has Str $.time;
    has Str $.restaurant;
    has Str $.date;
}
=end code

If the LLM produces C<party: 0> or C<party: 99>, object construction fails
with a clear type error rather than silently accepting bad data.

=head2 Seeing failure in action

=begin code :lang<raku>
# LLM normalized "a crowd" to: party many
my $m = Slangify::Tutorial::Grammar.parse(
    'name "X" party many time 19:00 restaurant "Y" date today'
);
say $m.so;   # False — grammar rejects non-numeric party
=end code

Readers love seeing failure B<and> correction. The grammar gives you both:
a clear rejection plus a single place to tighten the rule.

=head2 Preferred types

=defn integers
Use C<\d+> in the token and C<Int> in the class attribute.

=defn enums
Use alternation in the token: C<low | medium | high>.

=defn dates
Use a specific pattern token rather than bare C<\S+> if you need validation.

=defn free strings
Keep C<\S+> or C<< <-["]>+ >> but add C<Str> typing so at least the attribute is
defined.

=end pod
